At https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/61110
 Ed Tanous 

I have a minor preference for this one, because "invalid" means that the input was invalid, nullopt means there's no output.

Invalid is different than not present. But my preference here isn't strong; The only thing that's important is that we follow DBUS_USAGE.md as far as the user is concerned.

I think - in many places, bmcweb seems preferring like this coding style .
```
        if (endpoints.size() != 1)
        {
             if (endpoints.size() > 1)
             {
                  BMCWEB_LOG_ERROR
                      << "PCIeDevice is associated with more than one PCIeSlot: "
                      << endpoints.size();
                  messages::internalError(asyncResp->res);
                  return;
             }

             // If the device doesn't have an association, return without PCIe
            // Slot properties
            BMCWEB_LOG_DEBUG << "PCIeDevice is not associated with PCIeSlot";
            return;
        }
        //
        callback(endpoints[0]);
```

Should we define these like below?

```
    std::string* generation = nullptr;
    size_t* lanes = nullptr;
    std::string* slotType = nullptr;
```   

And then check them after calling `unpackPropertiesNoThrow()` to see whether they are obtained.
```
if(generation == nullptr) 
```

